# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: designated-hitter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:designated-hitter/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-boston-red-sox-season] The **1973 Boston Red Sox season** was the 73rd season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished second in the American League East with a record of 89 wins and 73 losses, eight games behind the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-boston-red-sox-season] The team was managed by Eddie Kasko until he was reassigned at the end of September; third-base coach Eddie Popowski managed the team in their final contest of the season.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The **1973 major league baseball season** began on April 5 while the regular season ended on October 1.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The 44th All-Star Game was held on July 24 at Royals Stadium in Kansas City, Missouri, home of the Kansas City Royals.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The National League won, 7–1, and was the second win in what would be a 10-win streak that lasted until 1983.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the designated hitter rule in the American League.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] American League umpires began wearing burgundy blazers with blue pants, a change from the navy blue coats and gray pants worn the previous five seasons (1968–1972).
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The burgundy blazers were worn through 1979.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] A lockout in the offseason (February 8–25) did not result in any regular season games being canceled, but the start of spring training was delayed.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The 1973 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 12 teams.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] Each league was split into two six-team divisions.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against their five division rivals, totaling 90 games, and 12 games against six interdivision opponents, totaling 72 games.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1969 and would be used until 1977 in the American League and 1993 in the National League.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 5, featuring a game between the Cincinnati Reds and Houston Astros, while National League Opening Day took place the following day, featuring eight teams.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] In a scheduling oddity, April 30 saw all teams not play, the last time all teams would be off (aside from All-Star breaks and labor shortages) until June 29, 1998.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the regular season on September 30, featuring 10 teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring four teams.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The National League Championship Series took place between October 6 and October 10, while the American League Championship Series took place between October 6 and October 11.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 13 and October 21.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] 1 tie game (0 in AL, 1 in NL), which is not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and was replayed again) occurred during the season.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 6 and ended on October 21 with the Oakland Athletics defeating the New York Mets in the 1973 World Series in seven games.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The Kansas City Royals leave Municipal Stadium from which they played four seasons and opened Royals Stadium, where they continue to play to the present day.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Yankees would play their final game at Yankee Stadium on September 30, in what would be a two year hiatus caused by renovations.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The team would play at Shea Stadium, the home of their cross-town rival New York Mets, before returning to a newly renovated Yankee Stadium in 1976.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-major-league-baseball-season] NBC was the exclusive national TV broadcaster of MLB, airing the weekend *Game of the Week*, *Monday Night Baseball*, the All-Star Game, both League Championship Series, and the World Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] The 1973 New York Yankees season was the 71st season for the team.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] The Yankees finished fourth in the American League East with a record of 80–82 under manager Ralph Houk, 17 games behind the division champion Baltimore Orioles.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] This was the last time that the Yankees finished the season below .500 until 1982.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] This was also their last year in the "old" Yankee Stadium (on the south side of 161st Street), which was targeted for major reconstruction in 1974–1975.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] During this period, the Yankees shared a home field with a National League team for the third time in their history, moving into Shea Stadium for two years.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] The Yankees had been struggling during their years under CBS ownership, which had acquired the team in 1965.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] Michael Burke the media company intended to sell the club.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] As Burke later told writer Roger Kahn, Paley offered to sell the franchise to Burke if he could find financial backing.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] Burke ran across Steinbrenner's name and veteran baseball executive Gabe Paul, a Cleveland-area acquaintance of Steinbrenner, helped bring the two men together.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] On January 3, 1973, a group of investors led by George Steinbrenner and minority partner Burke bought the Yankees from CBS for $10 million.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] The announced intention was that Burke would continue to run the team as club president.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] But Burke later became angry when he found out that Paul had been brought in as a senior Yankee executive, crowding his authority, and quit the team presidency on April 29, 1973.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] (Burke remained a minority owner of the club into the following decade.) He handed in his resignation to the New York Yankees, so that he could become president of Madison Square Garden.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] It would be the first of many high-profile departures by employees who crossed paths with "The Boss".
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] At the conclusion of the 1973 season, two more prominent names departed: manager Ralph Houk, who resigned and then signed to manage the Detroit Tigers; and general manager Lee MacPhail, who became president of the American League.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] After the last game of the 1973 season on September 30, fans ripped out parts of the stadium, including the seats, to take as souvenirs.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] The stadium would be remodeled, and reopen in 1976.
[src:designated-hitter/1973-new-york-yankees-season] On July 1, the Yankees were 45–33 and leading the American League East by four games, but posted a 35–49 record in their remaining games.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The **1976 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1976 season.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The 73rd edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff played between the National League (NL) champion Cincinnati Reds and the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Reds swept the Series in four games to repeat as champions, avenging their 1939 and 1961 World Series losses to the Yankees.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The 1976 Reds became, and remain, the only team to sweep an entire multi-tier postseason, one of the crowning achievements of the franchise's Big Red Machine era.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] They also became the third NL team (following the Chicago Cubs in 1907–08 and the New York Giants in 1921–22) to win consecutive World Series, and were the last to do so until the Los Angeles Dodgers in 2024–25.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] This was also the second time that the Yankees were swept in a World Series in four straight games, the Los Angeles Dodgers having previously done so in 1963.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] (The New York Giants "swept" them in five games in 1922, with Game 2 ending in a tie due to being called on account of darkness.) It was also the first World Series sweep in ten years, and the first for the Reds; their next came against the Oakland Athletics in 1990.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Reds won the NL West division by ten games over the Dodgers, then defeated the Philadelphia Phillies in three straight games in the NL Championship Series, after losing seven of twelve to them during the regular season.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Yankees won the AL East division by 10+1⁄2 games over the Baltimore Orioles, then defeated the Kansas City Royals in the deciding fifth game of the AL Championship Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The use of the DH wound up benefiting the Reds, who were able to get utility infielder Dan Driessen's bat in the lineup.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Elliott Maddox, Carlos May, and Lou Piniella shared the role for the Yankees, but were less productive.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Game 1, played at Cincinnati's Riverfront Stadium, marked the first time the DH was used in a NL ballpark.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Game 2, also at Riverfront Stadium, was the first World Series weekend game to be scheduled at night.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Reds catcher Johnny Bench was named the World Series MVP.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Bench batted .533 with 8 hits, 6 RBIs and two home runs and also scored 4 runs.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] After spending the last two years sharing home field with the New York Mets at Shea Stadium, the 1976 New York Yankees returned home to a rebuilt and modified Yankee Stadium.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] George Steinbrenner had now owned the team for four years, since 1973, with Billy Martin serving the first of his five stints as manager since 1975.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The heart of the team was Yankee captain, Thurman Munson, whose grit and determination were factors in his winning the 1976 American League MVP award.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Third baseman, Graig Nettles, and first baseman, Chris Chambliss were the key run producers, while speedy outfielders Roy White and Rivers set the table for the power hitters.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Super free agent Catfish Hunter headed the staff while reliever Sparky Lyle led the A.L. in saves with 23.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Yankees finished 10+1⁄2 ahead in the A.L.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] East advancing to the World Series by beating the Kansas City Royals in the fifth game of the playoffs on a ninth-inning walk-off home run by Chambliss.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The defending champion Cincinnati Reds were piloted by Sparky Anderson who had a star-studded lineup led by second baseman Joe Morgan.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Catcher Johnny Bench, first baseman Tony Perez, and outfielder George Foster provided enough power to drive in sparkplugs Pete Rose, Ken Griffey, and Morgan, who combined power (27 homers, 111 RBI) and speed (67 stolen bases) from the third-spot in the batting order.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Morgan went on to win his second-straight National League Most Valuable Player award, outdistancing runner-up teammate Foster.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Foster would go on to win the 1977 MVP award, giving the Reds six MVPs in an eight-year stretch.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Bench won MVP honors in 1970 and 1972 while Rose took home the hardware in '73.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Reds led the NL in every significant offensive category including runs scored, batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage, doubles, triples, home runs, RBI, and stolen bases.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] On the mound, the Reds relied on left-handers Don Gullett and Fred Norman to pacify the Yankee hitters in Games 1 and 2, respectively.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Gullett had come back from a mid-season injury to start Game 1 but had to leave the game in the eighth inning due to a twisted ankle while Norman out-pitched ace Hunter in Game 2.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Game 3 in New York pitted effective 1976 NL Rookie of the Year Pat Zachry for the Reds against newly acquired Yankee, Dock Ellis.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Ellis only lasted 3+1⁄3 innings, exiting in the fourth after a home run by Driessen.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Game 4 was delayed a day due to rain, but the Reds were ready for the sweep.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Bench's two-run home run gave the Reds a 3–1 lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] In the top of the ninth, a frustrated Billy Martin threw a baseball from the dugout onto the field towards home plate umpire Bill Deegan, causing his ejection from the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] In the ninth, Bench's second home run followed by back-to-back doubles by César Gerónimo and Dave Concepción made the score 7–2 and essentially blew the game open.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Cincinnati Reds outscored the New York Yankees, 22–8, and became the first NL team to repeat as World Champions since the 1921–1922 New York Giants.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Reds did not make a single offensive or defensive substitution (save pitching changes) during the entire series.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Bench would claim the MVP of the series hitting .533 with two home runs and six runs batted in.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] His catching counterpart, Thurman Munson, had nine hits, all singles, and a .529 batting average.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Joe Morgan got the Reds off to a booming start with a home run in the first off of Doyle Alexander, who had to start because Catfish Hunter had a sore arm and needed another day of rest.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Yankees tied the game in the second when Lou Piniella hit a leadoff double, moved to third on a groundout and scored on Graig Nettles's sacrifice fly.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] In the third, Dave Concepcion tripled with one out and scored on Pete Rose's sacrifice fly to put the Reds up 2–1.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Tony Pérez's RBI single in the sixth extended their lead to 3–1.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] In the seventh, George Foster hit a leadoff single and scored on a Johnny Bench RBI triple.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Bench then scored on a Sparky Lyle wild pitch.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The only bad news for the Reds was an injury to starting pitcher Don Gullett, who pulled a calf muscle in the eighth and would be unavailable for the remainder of the Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] It turned out to be Gullett's last appearance in a Reds uniform.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Pedro Borbon pitched 1+2⁄3 shutout innings to close the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Reds scored three runs in the second off Catfish Hunter.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] After a leadoff double by Dan Driessen, George Foster's RBI single put the Reds up 1–0.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Foster was caught stealing second, but after a double and walk, Dave Concepción's RBI single made it 2–0 Reds.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] A walk loaded the bases before a sacrifice fly by Ken Griffey made it 3–0 Reds.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Yankees got on the board on an RBI single by Graig Nettles in the fourth.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] In the seventh, the Yankees tied things up on an RBI double by Fred Stanley off starter Fred Norman and an RBI groundout by Thurman Munson off Jack Billingham.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Meanwhile, Hunter settled into a groove, pitching a complete game and shutting out the Reds until the ninth.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] With two outs, Ken Griffey reached second when Stanley threw wildly past first after fielding his slow bouncer.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Joe Morgan was walked intentionally and Tony Pérez ended the game by driving in Griffey with a single.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Sunday night contest, the first weekend World Series game to begin after dark, was played under temperatures that started at 43 °F (6 °C) and dipped into the 30s as the game progressed.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Major League Baseball commissioner Bowie Kuhn responded to criticism of the scheduling, which was done to accommodate NBC television, by attending the game without wearing an overcoat in spite of the cold nighttime weather.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] As the Series moved to Yankee Stadium, the Reds struck first with three runs off starter Dock Ellis.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Dan Driessen hit a leadoff single, stole second and scored on an RBI double by George Foster, After Johnny Bench singled, an RBI force-out by César Gerónimo made it 2–0 Reds.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Geronimo stole second and scored on an RBI single by Dave Concepción to cap the inning's scoring.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Dan Driessen smacked a home run in the fourth.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, the Yankees got on the board on Oscar Gamble's single off of Pat Zachry.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] A seventh inning home run by Jim Mason—the 500th home run in the history of the World Series—cut the Reds' lead to 4–2.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Mason became the first of two players to hit a home run in his only World Series at-bat, the second being Geoff Blum in 2005 for the Chicago White Sox.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Reds got both runs back in the eighth on Joe Morgan's RBI double off Grant Jackson after two leadoff singles and Foster's RBI single off Dick Tidrow.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] This game featured a slick defensive play by Grant Jackson in the top of the seventh.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Johnny Bench hit a hard grounder up the middle which appeared to be a sure base hit, but Jackson speared the ball with his glove behind his back and retired Bench.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] This was the first World Series game at Yankee Stadium to open with opera star Robert Merrill's famous rendition of the National Anthem.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Yankees got on the board in the first (which would be their only lead in this Series) on a two-out Thurman Munson single and a Chris Chambliss double off of Gary Nolan.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Munson would collect four hits in the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] In the fourth, Joe Morgan walked off of Ed Figueroa, stole second, and came home on a George Foster single.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Johnny Bench followed with his first home run to give the Reds a 3–1 lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] The Yankees cut the lead to 3–2 in the fifth inning when Mickey Rivers hit a leadoff single, stole second and scored on Munson's single, but the Reds padded that lead in the ninth.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Figueroa walked two before being relieved by Dick Tidrow, who allowed a one-out three-run home run to Bench to extend the Reds' lead to 6–2.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] César Gerónimo and Dave Concepción followed with consecutive doubles to make 7–2 Reds.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] Will McEnaney pitched 2+1⁄3 shutout innings to end the series.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] It was the Reds' second-straight World Series victory and the second-straight time McEnaney would be on the mound for the Series' final out.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] It also, to date, is the only perfect playoff season since the LCS was created in 1969.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] This was Tony Perez's final game in a Reds uniform until 1984.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] With the win, the Reds became the first visiting team since the 1957 Milwaukee Braves to win the World Series at Yankee Stadium.
[src:designated-hitter/1976-world-series] This was the first of 21 consecutive World Series to be broadcast by CBS Radio.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The **1985 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1985 season.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The 82nd edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff played between the American League (AL) champion Kansas City Royals and the National League (NL) champion St.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals upset the heavily favored Cardinals in seven games.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Series was popularly known as the "**Show-Me Series**" or the "**I-70 Showdown Series**," as both cities are in the state of Missouri which is nicknamed the "Show Me State" and are connected by Interstate 70.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals won the NL East division by three games over the New York Mets, then defeated the Los Angeles Dodgers four games to two in the NL Championship Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals won the AL West division by one game over the California Angels, then defeated the Toronto Blue Jays four games to three in the AL Championship Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals were seeking to win their NL-leading 10th World Series title, while the Royals were seeking their first World Series title.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals were completing one of the most successful decades by any expansion team, with six division titles and two pennants from 1976 to 1985.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] This was the first World Series in which all games were played at night.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Also, this was the second all-Missouri World Series; the first in 1944 was all-St.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Louis series between the Cardinals and Browns (a decade later, they became the Baltimore Orioles).
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] This was the second of five World Series played completely on artificial turf; the first was in 1980 and the others were in 1987, 1993 and 2020.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] This is the most recent World Series in which the designated hitter was not used in an AL baseball park.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] From 1976 to 1985, the DH was used in all games in even-numbered years.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In odd-numbered years, like this World Series, the pitchers from both were required to bat for themselves throughout the series, as in the National League.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Beginning with the next World Series, the DH rule was used only at the AL representative's park.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The 1985 World Series is best remembered for an incorrect safe call made by first base umpire Don Denkinger in Game 6.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Louis leading the World Series 3-2 and in possession of a 1-0 lead in the bottom of the ninth inning, Denkinger incorrectly called Jorge Orta safe.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals won the game 2-1 on a two-run walk-off single and then won Game 7 by a score of 11-0.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] This also later happened in the 1996 World Series, where the New York Yankees defeated the Atlanta Braves after losing the first two games at home.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] It is the last time this happened in a World Series, but the Toronto Blue Jays accomplished the feat against the Seattle Mariners in the 2025 American League Championship Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Bret Saberhagen's victories in Games 3 and 7, allowing only a single run across his two starts, earned him the World Series Most Valuable Player Award.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In their 17th season, the Royals won their first World Series title; their next appearance was 29 years later in 2014 against the San Francisco Giants, but they lost in seven games.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] A year later, the Royals won their second title, over the New York Mets.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] This was the first World Series to have all games played at night during primetime, however this would become a regular practice until 1990 when the games would start at 8pm eastern.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] When Lonnie Smith led off for the Royals, he became the first player in MLB history to be traded from a team (the Cardinals) during a season and play against that team in the World Series the same season.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] John Tudor scattered seven hits in 6+2⁄3 innings for the Cards and won with relief help from Todd Worrell.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals struck first in the second on Steve Balboni's RBI single with runners on first and second, but the Cardinals tied it off of Danny Jackson in the third on Willie McGee's RBI groundout with runners on second and third.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Next inning, Tito Landrum doubled with one out, then scored on late-season acquisition César Cedeño's RBI double to give Jackson the loss despite Jackson throwing seven innings of two-run ball.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals padded their lead in the ninth off of Dan Quisenberry when Tom Herr singled to lead off and scored on Jack Clark's double.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] This was the first Saturday night game in World Series history.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Series began on a Saturday from 1969 through 1976, and again from 1985 through 2006 (with the exception of 1990, which began on a Tuesday night).
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals went up 2–0 in the fourth off of Danny Cox when Willie Wilson hit a leadoff single that was followed by back-to-back RBI doubles by George Brett and Frank White.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] However Charlie Leibrandt continued a history of tough luck in the postseason.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The previous year, he had lost Game 3 of the 1984 ALCS, 1–0, to the Detroit Tigers when he pitched a three-hit complete game.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] He lost Game 4 in the 1985 ALCS in the ninth inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Clinging to a two-run lead in the ninth of this game, manager Dick Howser opted to not send in his relief ace Dan Quisenberry to close out the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Leibrandt allowed a leadoff double to Willie McGee, then was only one out from tying the series at one apiece when he allowed an RBI single to Jack Clark.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] After a double and walk loaded the bases, Terry Pendleton cleared them with a double and gave the Cardinals a 4–2 lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Quisenberry came in and after he walked Darrell Porter he got out of the inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Jeff Lahti earned a save with a scoreless bottom of the inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals' four run ninth would be the only inning in the series in which they scored more than one run.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals got back into the series by riding ace Bret Saberhagen to a 6–1 victory against twenty-game winner Joaquín Andújar.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Saberhagen flashed messages on the television screen to his pregnant wife who was due to give birth any day.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] She eventually gave birth on October 26 (in Game 6).
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals went up 2–0 in the fourth on Lonnie Smith's two-run double that scored Jim Sundberg and Buddy Biancalana, who had walked and singled, respectively.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Royals second baseman Frank White made history by becoming the first second baseman in the history of the World Series to hit in the clean-up spot in the batting order.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] White came through with a two-run home run off of Andújar in the fifth after George Brett got on base.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals scored their only run of the game in the sixth off of Saberhagen on consecutive singles by Ozzie Smith, Tom Herr, and Jack Clark.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals padded their lead in the seventh off of Ricky Horton when George Brett drew a leadoff walk, moved to second on a balk, then scored on White's double.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Two outs later, White scored on Biancalana's single to cap the scoring.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] John Tudor's complete game shutout put the Cardinals on the verge of winning their second World Series in four years.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Tito Landrum, only playing due to a tarp injury to Vince Coleman, continued to make his case for series MVP with a home run in the second off of Bud Black.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Next inning, Willie McGee homered also to make it 2–0 Cardinals, who added to their lead in the fifth when Terry Pendleton tripled with one out and scored on Black's throwing error on Tom Nieto's bunt attempt.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The best chance for the Royals to score was in the seventh inning, when they loaded the bases on two singles and a walk.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] With pinch-hitter Hal McRae up for Buddy Biancalana, he grounded to the third baseman to end the threat.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Tudor allowed just five hits in a complete game while striking out eight with one walk while Black went just five innings and allowing three runs on four hits and three walks.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Entering this game, the Royals were 3–0 in must-win games in playoff elimination games.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] They improved their record to 4–0 with a decisive victory over the Cardinals, again by the score of 6–1.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals struck first on Frank White's groundout with runners on second and third in the top of the first off of Bob Forsch, but the Cardinals tied it off of Danny Jackson in the bottom half on back-to-back two-out doubles by Tom Herr and Jack Clark.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] However, they would not score after that.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals broke the game open in the second when Buddy Biancalana singled to score Jim Sundberg, who doubled with one out.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] After Lonnie Smith walked, Willie Wilson tripled home both runs to make it 4–1.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals added to their lead in the eighth off of Jeff Lahti on shortstop Ozzie Smith's throwing error on Danny Jackson's ground ball, then in the ninth on Pat Sheridan's RBI double.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Jackson was the winning pitcher, following the same formula and pitching rotation as the Royals did in the ALCS where Jackson also won Game 5.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Jackson threw an immaculate inning in the 7th, becoming the only pitcher to do so during a postseason game to date.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Jackson scattered five hits, allowing only one run in a complete game.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] A pitcher's duel unfolded between Danny Cox and Charlie Leibrandt, the tough-luck loser in Game 2.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In the fourth inning of the scoreless game, the Royals' Frank White may have stolen second base, but was ruled out in a close call.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The batter, Pat Sheridan, hit a single to right field two pitches later.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] If White had been on base when Sheridan singled, the Royals would have likely taken a 1–0 lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Instead, Leibrandt and Cox traded scoreless innings until the eighth, when pinch-hitter Brian Harper singled home Terry Pendleton, who had singled earlier, to give the Cardinals a 1–0 lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals' 1–0 lead entering the bottom of the eighth was the result of St.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Louis taking the upper hand after two situations that were mirror images of each other: In consecutive half-innings – the bottom of the seventh and the top of the eighth – both teams had runners on first and second with their respective starting pitcher coming to bat.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Kansas City manager Dick Howser opted to leave Leibrandt in the game to bat, but the Royals starter struck out to end the inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In contrast, Whitey Herzog pulled Cardinals starter Cox for pinch hitter Harper, who then had the game's first hit with runners in scoring position to put St.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, Herzog called on rookie reliever Todd Worrell to relieve setup man Ken Dayley, who had pitched the eighth and would have been the winner had the Cardinals won.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The first batter, pinch-hitter Jorge Orta, sent a chopping bouncer to the right of Jack Clark.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] He tossed the ball to Worrell, who tagged the bag ahead of Orta, but Clark's toss was behind Worrell, causing the running Orta to come between umpire Don Denkinger and his view of the lunging Worrell's glove.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] TV replays – not used by officials for play review until 2008 – indicated that Orta should have been called out, and an argument ensued on the field.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals argued briefly, but as crew chief and believing he had made the correct call, Denkinger did not reverse it.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In his book *You're Missing a Great Game*, Herzog wrote that he later wished he had asked Commissioner Peter Ueberroth, who was in attendance, to overrule the call and declare Orta out.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] If Ueberroth had refused to do so, Herzog would have pulled his team from the field and forfeited the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Instead of one out and no one on, the Royals now had no outs and a runner on first for batter Steve Balboni.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Balboni lifted a pop-up in foul territory along the edge of the first base dugout.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Jack Clark, who had only recently made the transition from right field to first base that season, lost track of the ball as he looked to find the dugout and the ball dropped on the top step of the dugout.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Balboni then singled two pitches later, putting runners at first and second with nobody out.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Onix Concepción was sent in as a pinch runner for the slow-footed Balboni.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Catcher Jim Sundberg attempted to sacrifice the runners over, but he failed.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] With two strikes, he bunted anyway, and sent it back to Worrell, who threw to third to force out Orta, the only out the Cardinals would record.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Darrell Porter then allowed a passed ball, advancing Concepción and Sundberg to third and second, respectively.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] With first base now open and two runners in scoring position, Herzog then chose to walk Royals pinch hitter Hal McRae to set up a potential double play.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] McRae was replaced by the faster John Wathan to pinch-run to avoid a potential double play.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] With the bases loaded and one out, Royals pinch hitter Dane Iorg (a former Cardinal who had won a championship ring with them in 1982) blooped a single to right field.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Concepción scored the tying run and Sundberg approached the plate with the winning run.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Right fielder Andy Van Slyke's throw was on target, but Sundberg slid home safely with the game-winning run.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals celebrated the rally, and mobbed home plate.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals went to their dressing rooms, only to find champagne waiting for them and plastic over their lockers in anticipation for the celebration that never came.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Denkinger stated that he still believed he had made the right call until he later met with Commissioner Peter Ueberroth after the game and had the opportunity to see the replay himself.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] He would later claim that he was waiting to hear the ball land in Worrell's glove while watching the bag for Orta's foot.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Due to the crowd noise in Royals Stadium, he ruled Orta safe because he never heard Worrell catch the ball.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] "I was in good position, but Worrell is tall, the throw was high, and I couldn't watch his glove and his feet at the same time," Denkinger told *Sports Illustrated*.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Denkinger was scheduled to be the home plate umpire in Game 7.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] One night after becoming a father, Bret Saberhagen tossed a five-hitter and got all the offense he needed when Darryl Motley homered to left off John Tudor in the second inning, after a walk to Steve Balboni.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In the third, Lonnie Smith led off with a walk, and with one out George Brett hit an infield single.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] After a double steal, Tudor issued walks to Frank White to load the bases and Jim Sundberg to force in Smith, making it 3–0.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Tudor was replaced with Bill Campbell after only 2+1⁄3 innings.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Balboni singled to left off Campbell to score Brett and White to make it 5–0.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Tudor walked four and was charged with all five runs.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In the dugout, he angrily punched an electrical fan, cutting his pitching hand.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals blew the game open in the bottom of the fifth.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] A succession of five Cardinal pitchers allowed six Royals runs, five coming after two were out.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Campbell gave up a single to Sundberg and was immediately replaced by Jeff Lahti, who allowed four hits to score four runs before being replaced by Ricky Horton.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] After Horton gave up a single to Brett and fell behind on the count 2-0 to Frank White, Herzog replaced him with Joaquín Andújar, normally a starter but pressed into relief.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Andújar allowed an RBI single to White, increasing the Royals lead to 10–0.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] With Sundberg at the plate (the Royals had batted around), Andújar twice charged home plate umpire Denkinger to disagree with his strike zone.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] First, Denkinger called an Andújar pitch a ball.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] ABC's Tim McCarver mistakenly said it was the second, after 1969.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The next pitch was also called a ball to walk Sundberg, and Denkinger ejected Andújar, who then charged at Denkinger.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] It took three teammates to restrain him and get him off the field.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Andújar was suspended for the first ten games of the 1986 season for his outburst.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Although it has been rumored that Herzog sent in Andújar specifically to bait Denkinger, Herzog himself has said several times that Andújar was the only pitcher who still had anything left in his arm.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] After Game 5 loser Bob Forsch's first pitch was wild to score Brett, he got out of the fifth-inning nightmare.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] He pitched a clean sixth inning and Ken Dayley kept the Royals off the scoreboard for the last two innings, but it was not enough as the Cardinals could not score against Saberhagen.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals' .185 batting average was the lowest for a seven-game World Series until the New York Yankees hit .183 in the 2001 World Series against the Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals also scored only thirteen total runs—an all-time low for a seven-game series—scoring only once in the final 26 innings of the series.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] If they had held on for the win in Game 6, they still would have been outscored in the series 15–13.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] This was Kansas City's second major professional sports championship, joining the Chiefs' victory in Super Bowl IV in January 1970.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] These franchises have since added four more championships, with the Royals winning the 2015 World Series, and the Chiefs winning Super Bowls LIV, LVII and LVIII.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] ABC televised the series, with play-by-play announcer Al Michaels and color commentators Jim Palmer and Tim McCarver.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] This was the first World Series broadcast for McCarver, who would go on to call a record 24 World Series telecasts with ABC, CBS and Fox.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Howard Cosell was originally scheduled to be in the booth with Michaels and Palmer, but was removed from his assignment just prior to Game 1 because of the controversy surrounding his book *I Never Played the Game*.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] ABC's coverage was simulcast in Canada on the Global Television Network.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] CBS Radio broadcast the series nationally, with Jack Buck on play-by-play and Sparky Anderson providing color commentary.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Locally, Royals' flagship station WIBW (Topeka) aired the games in Kansas City with Denny Matthews and Fred White alternating on play-by-play and color, while in St.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Louis the Cardinals' flagship KMOX simulcast the CBS Radio coverage due to Buck's status as the team's primary local announcer during the regular season, although regular analyst Mike Shannon was sidelined in favor of Anderson.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals became the first team ever to win the World Series after losing the first two games at home.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The following year, the New York Mets accomplished the same feat by defeating the Boston Red Sox in seven games in the World Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In the 1996 World Series, the New York Yankees lost their first two games at home against the defending 1995 World Series champion Atlanta Braves before winning four straight to claim the title.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals also were the fifth team in MLB history to come back from a 3–1 deficit to win a best-of-seven World Series, the previous teams being the 1925 Pittsburgh Pirates, 1958 New York Yankees, 1968 Detroit Tigers, and the 1979 Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The 1985 Royals had also come back from a three games to one deficit to win the American League Championship Series against the Toronto Blue Jays, making them the first and so far only team to do so (the championship series had changed from a best-of-five to a best-of-seven format in 1985).
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The six elimination games won by the Royals represent a Major League record for a single postseason, a record which would later be equaled by the 2012 San Francisco Giants.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals also became the first team to win two Game 7s in one postseason.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The 2017 Houston Astros are the only other team to achieve this feat.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In the immediate aftermath of the 1985 World Series, umpire Don Denkinger received many hateful letters from Cardinals fans due to his blown call in Game 6 that essentially cost the Cardinals a World Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Denkinger contacted Major League Baseball Security, which in turn contacted the FBI, when he received a particularly menacing letter with no return address that said that if the writer saw Denkinger in person, he would "blow him away" with a .357 Magnum.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] According to Denkinger, FBI agents visited the letter writer and told him, "You're done.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Denkinger had other big umpiring assignments after the 1985 Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] He was behind the plate for the All-Star Game the following season, and he was named crew chief for the 1988 ALCS, 1991 World Series, and 1992 ALCS.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] He retired in 1998, ironically with his last game being at Kauffman Stadium on June 2, 1998.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] After retirement, Denkinger would lean into his fame of the blown call, regularly appearing at sports memorabilia shows (including ones in St.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Louis) willing to autograph photos depicting "The Call".
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Nevertheless, many publications consider his blown call in Game 6 of the 1985 World Series one of the biggest umpire blunders in MLB history.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In 1987, the Cardinals won the NLCS in seven games over the San Francisco Giants.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] In the World Series against the Minnesota Twins, after having fallen behind 2-0 at the Hubert H.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Humphrey Metrodome, they won their next three games at home.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] However, back at the Metrodome, they lost the last two and again fell one game short of a World Series title.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] It would be the Cardinals' last World Series appearance until 2004.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Cardinals did not win another World Series until 2006.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The Royals did not play in another postseason game until the 2014 American League Wild Card Game, and did not win another World Series until the following season, in 2015.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] The introduction of interleague play to major league baseball in 1997 allowed the I-70 Series to be revived in regular season games each year.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Through the 2022 season, the Cardinals lead the regular-season interleague series, 73-47, though Kansas City still holds the World Series win over St.
[src:designated-hitter/1985-world-series] Louis, as it was the last and only time the two teams have faced off in the postseason.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The **1986 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1986 season.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The 83rd edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff played between the National League (NL) champion New York Mets and the American League (AL) champion Boston Red Sox.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Mets won the series in seven games, claiming their second World Series title and first since 1969.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The series is best remembered for its Game 6, which saw the Mets rally from a two-run deficit in the bottom of the 10th inning, despite having two outs and no one on base.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Red Sox, who held a 3–2 series lead, were twice one strike away from securing the championship, but failed to close out the inning as the Mets won off an error by Boston first baseman Bill Buckner.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] When the Mets won the series in Game 7, the Game 6 collapse entered baseball lore as part of the Curse of the Bambino superstition used to explain the Red Sox's championship drought between 1918 and 2004.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The 1986 World Series marked the second time, after the previous year's series, in which the winning team lost the first two games of the series at home (the Kansas City Royals accomplished this the year prior).
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] It happened again in the 1996 World Series with the New York Yankees, the last such World Series occurrence, but it would happen in the 2025 American League Championship Series with the Toronto Blue Jays.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] This was the fifth meeting between teams from Boston and New York City for a major professional sports championship.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] This previously occurred in two Stanley Cup Finals (1929, 1972) and two previous World Series (1912, 1916).
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The New York Mets finished the regular season with a franchise-best record of 108–54, winning the National League East division by 21+1⁄2 games over the division rival Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] They then won a tightly contested 1986 National League Championship Series against the Houston Astros, 4 games to 2, clinching the series with a 7–6, 16-inning win in Game 6.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] On July 19, Mets' infielder Tim Teufel and pitchers Rick Aguilera, Bobby Ojeda, and Ron Darling were arrested after fighting with policemen outside a bar in Houston.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Despite the adversity, the Mets won the game, 6–3 in 14 innings, on a three-run homer by Howard Johnson.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Boston went 95–66 during the season, winning the American League East division by 5+1⁄2 games over their biggest nemesis, the New York Yankees, marking the first time since 1904 that the Red Sox and the Yankees finished first and second in the standings.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The team's defining moment occurred in Game 5 of the 1986 American League Championship Series against the California Angels.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Angels never recovered from this blow, and with Boston capitalizing on some defensive miscues by the Angels, and clutch performances by some of their big name players (namely Rice and Clemens in the deciding game), the Red Sox clinched the pennant with a seven-game series win.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Just as they did against Houston in the National League Championship Series, the Mets opened the World Series by taking a 1–0 defeat.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Boston's Bruce Hurst dominated the Mets with his forkball and looping curve, allowing only four hits over eight innings to get the win.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the bottom of the sixth, Hurst got Ray Knight to ground into an inning-ending double play and thwart a scoring opportunity for the Mets.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] New York's Ron Darling was equally effective, yielding only one unearned run in the seventh inning when second baseman Tim Teufel committed an error by letting a ground ball from Rich Gedman go through his legs, allowing Jim Rice to score from second.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Red Sox closer Calvin Schiraldi, acquired from the Mets in the previous offseason, walked Darryl Strawberry to lead off the bottom of the ninth inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] However, Schiraldi got Knight to force out Strawberry at second base and then got Wally Backman to fly out to left field.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] With two outs, Danny Heep pinch hit for Rafael Santana.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Schiraldi worked Heep to a 2–2 count and then struck him out swinging to solidify the victory.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Mets' legend Tom Seaver, now a member of the Red Sox, received a standing ovation from the Shea Stadium fans during the Game 1 introductions.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Seaver did not pitch in the series because of a knee injury.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Game 2 figured to be a classic pitching matchup, between the Mets' young phenom Dwight Gooden and Boston's own young pitching sensation Roger Clemens, but neither pitcher went beyond five innings.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Red Sox scored first in the top of the third inning, following a leadoff walk to Spike Owen, when Keith Hernandez fielded a Clemens bunt, but threw it away trying to catch Owen at second base.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Wade Boggs then drove in Owen with a double, Marty Barrett drove in Clemens with a single, and Bill Buckner drove in Boggs with a single to give the Sox a 3–0 lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the bottom half of the inning, the Mets had men on second and third base for Wally Backman, who grounded up the middle, plating Rafael Santana.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Hernandez then grounded out, allowing Gooden to score and bring the Mets within one run.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the top of the fourth inning, Dave Henderson, the hero of the ALCS, drove the second pitch from Gooden to left-center field for a home run.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Dwight Evans followed with a two-run home run in the top of the fifth inning, bringing the score to 6–2.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Although Clemens had a comfortable lead going into the bottom of the fifth, he was pulled in favor of Steve Crawford after facing three batters, leaving runners on first and third.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Crawford promptly gave up a single to Gary Carter that scored Backman, cutting the deficit to three runs.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Crawford struck out Darryl Strawberry and got Danny Heep to ground out, but this left Clemens with a no decision.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Gooden was relieved by Rick Aguilera in the sixth inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Aguilera loaded the bases in the seventh, and after consecutive RBI singles by Henderson and Owen, was pulled in favor of Jesse Orosco, who shut down the Red Sox over the next two innings.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Facing Sid Fernandez, pitching in relief with runners on first and second base in the ninth inning, Boggs drove in Henderson with a double to make the score 9–3.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Mets were unable to recover from this deficit, and took the loss, giving Boston a 2–0 advantage heading to Fenway Park.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Mets manager Davey Johnson gave his team a day off from practice and interviews with the media just before game 3, thinking it would make his team more focused and re-energize them after their exhausting NLCS win over the Astros.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Johnson's plan worked as the Mets started well when Lenny Dykstra led off the game with a home run.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After two singles, Gary Carter followed with an RBI double, and Danny Heep drove in two runners with a single to give the Mets a 4–0 lead in the first inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After the rocky start, Red Sox starter Oil Can Boyd settled down, but Bob Ojeda pitched well and Boston was unable to overcome their early deficit.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In his first at bat of the World Series, Boston's Don Baylor almost homered in the second inning but hit the Green Monster, resulting in a double.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Ojeda gave up an RBI single to Marty Barrett in the bottom of the third inning, but this would be the only Boston run of the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Carter drove in two runners with a bases-loaded single in the seventh inning, and Ray Knight drove in Darryl Strawberry, who had singled and moved to third on two wild pitches, with a double in the eighth inning off of Joe Sambito.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Roger McDowell pitched the final two frames to seal a 7–1 Mets victory.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Ron Darling faced off against Boston's Al Nipper, as the Mets looked to tie the Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Neither starter allowed a run until the top of the fourth inning, when Gary Carter ripped a two-run home run over the Green Monster and Ray Knight drove in Darryl Strawberry, who had doubled after the home run, with a single.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the top of the seventh inning, Boston right fielder Dwight Evans almost robbed Lenny Dykstra of a two-run home run only for the ball to bounce out of his glove and over the wall.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] TV replay showed Evans taking off his hat and leaning against the wall in disappointment and frustration.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Carter hit a solo shot in the top of the eighth inning, both Dykstra's and Carter's second home run came off of Steve Crawford.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the eighth inning, the Red Sox scored two runs on an Evans single and a Dave Henderson sacrifice fly off of Roger McDowell, but it was not enough, and the Mets evened the series at two games apiece to ensure a return to New York.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Red Sox struck first in the second when Dave Henderson tripled with one out off of Dwight Gooden and scored on Spike Owen's sacrifice fly.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Dwight Evans's RBI single next inning with two on made it 2–0 Red Sox.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the fifth, Jim Rice hit a leadoff triple and scored on Don Baylor's single.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After Evans singled, Sid Fernandez relieved Gooden and allowed an RBI double to Henderson.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Bruce Hurst pitched 7+1⁄3 shutout innings before Tim Teufel's home run in the eighth put the Mets on the board.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the ninth, Mookie Wilson doubled with two outs and scored on Rafael Santana's single before Hurst struck out Lenny Dykstra to end the game as the Red Sox's 4–2 gave them a 3–2 series lead heading back to New York.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The series returned to Shea Stadium for Game 6 with the Mets facing elimination.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Bob Ojeda, the winner of Game 3, returned to the mound for New York.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Red Sox countered with Roger Clemens, who despite the team's victory in his Game 2 start did not factor into the decision as he was pulled from the game in the fifth inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The game was briefly paused in the top of the first, with Bill Buckner at bat, as actor and Mets fan Michael Sergio parachuted onto the field wearing a flag reading "Go Mets".
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He was immediately arrested by security after landing.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the first two innings, Boston took a quick 2–0 lead on RBI base hits from Dwight Evans and Marty Barrett.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Those would be the only runs Ojeda allowed in six innings.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Mets tied the score in the fifth inning on a single from Ray Knight and a run-scoring double play by Danny Heep, in his last at-bat as a Met.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After the Mets left the go-ahead run on base in the sixth, the Red Sox came to bat in the top of the seventh against New York reliever Roger McDowell.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Barrett started off the inning by drawing a walk, then advanced to second on a groundout by Bill Buckner.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Jim Rice then hit a ground ball to third that Knight misplayed, putting runners on the corners with one out.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] McDowell then got Evans to ground out to the left side, but since Boston had called for a hit-and-run, the Mets were unable to convert a double play and get out of the inning; Barrett scored on the groundout to give the Red Sox the lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Mets avoided further damage, though, as Rice was thrown out at home after trying to score from second on a single by Rich Gedman for the third out.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the top of the eighth, McDowell walked Dave Henderson to start the inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After Spike Owen laid down a sacrifice bunt, advancing Henderson to second, the pitcher's spot was due next.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Although Clemens had struck out eight Mets batters and had only allowed one earned run to this point in the game, manager John McNamara decided to call for a pinch hitter.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Despite having power hitting veteran Don Baylor on his bench, McNamara chose to send up rookie Mike Greenwell as he felt the matchup against McDowell favored him.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Greenwell responded by striking out on three pitches.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After intentionally walking Wade Boggs next, McDowell walked Barrett to load the bases.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Jesse Orosco came in to face Buckner, inducing a first-pitch fly out to end the inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] It was initially said that Clemens was removed from the game due to a blister forming on one of his fingers, but both he and McNamara dispute this.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Clemens said to Bob Costas on an MLB Network program concerning the 1986 postseason that McNamara decided to pull him despite Clemens wanting to pitch.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] McNamara said to Costas that Clemens "begged out" of the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Regardless of who was really telling the truth, the Red Sox had been warming up closer Calvin Schiraldi in the prior innings and, with him ready, McNamara brought him in to pitch the eighth.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Pinch hitter Lee Mazzilli, batting for Orosco, led off the inning with a single.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Lenny Dykstra then reached on an attempted sacrifice to put two runners on.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Wally Backman followed with another bunt to move Mazzilli and Dykstra into scoring position, and Schiraldi intentionally walked Keith Hernandez to load the bases for Gary Carter.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Schiraldi ran up a 3–0 count on Carter, but Carter swung at the next pitch and flied to left, deep enough to score Mazzilli and tie the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] With Dykstra now on third, Darryl Strawberry stood in with a chance to drive in the go-ahead run, but flied out to end the inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After the Red Sox failed to score against Rick Aguilera in the top of the ninth, the Mets came up with a chance to win the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Knight started the inning by drawing a walk off Schiraldi.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Mookie Wilson was then asked to lay down a bunt to try to move the runner up to second.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The bunt landed directly in front of home plate and catcher Gedman saw he had a play at second and threw there to try and get the lead runner.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] His throw was high, however, and pulled shortstop Owen off the base long enough for Knight to slide in safely.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Owen, Barrett, and McNamara argued that second base umpire Jim Evans made the wrong call, with McNamara saying he could not have seen Owen's foot land back on the bag, but television replays showed that Knight's hand touched just before Owen got his foot back down.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] With a runner now in scoring position and still nobody out, Howard Johnson came on to pinch hit.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Mets manager Davey Johnson had been expected by the Red Sox to call for a bunt in order to move Knight to third base, where he could score on a deep fly ball, but the play was not called and Johnson struck out.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Schiraldi then got Mazzilli out on a fly ball to left, failing to advance Knight to third, and followed that up with another fly out off the bat of Dykstra to end the inning and move the game to extra innings.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the visiting tenth, Henderson hit Aguilera's second pitch of the inning out of the park for a 4–3 Boston lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After getting Owen to strike out, the first of two opportunities for McNamara to utilize his bench, where he had several pinch-hitting options including Baylor still available, came up with the pitcher's spot now due.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] McNamara, however, sent Schiraldi to the plate despite having both Joe Sambito and Bob Stanley, the latter having not recorded a single earned run in the postseason to that point, in the bullpen ready to go.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Aguilera retired Schiraldi on a strikeout for the second out.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Boggs then followed with a double, and Barrett drove him in with a single to give the Red Sox an insurance run and a 5–3 lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The second chance for McNamara to use his bench followed.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The veteran first baseman Buckner was the next batter, and in many cases where Boston would be leading late in games McNamara would take Buckner out and replace him with Dave Stapleton at first base, as he had done in all three previous Red Sox victories in this series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] This time, he did not, even after Aguilera drilled the veteran first baseman in the hip with a pitch.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Rice, the next batter, ended the inning with a flyout to Mazzilli.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] When asked later about his decision to leave Buckner in the game, McNamara initially said that he felt that he deserved to stay on the field for the potential final out to preserve the victory and the championship.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Buckner, after all, was the third-oldest Red Sox player behind Baylor and Tom Seaver (who was not on the postseason roster), and was an 18-year veteran who had only seen action in one prior World Series, which came when he was a member of the Los Angeles Dodgers in the 1974 World Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Needing to rally for the second time in three innings, and now having to overcome a two-run deficit, the Mets' first two batters in the tenth went quietly against Schiraldi.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Backman flew out to left, and Hernandez flew out to center.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] With Carter now New York's last hope, the words "Congratulations Boston Red Sox, 1986 World Champions" briefly and accidentally flashed on the scoreboard.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The celebration, however, was put on hold as Carter singled to bring the tying run to the plate.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Had he not come out in the ninth inning, Strawberry would have been the next batter.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Hernandez, who had himself gone to the clubhouse after recording the second out, later said on a 2023 episode of *The Rich Eisen Show* that the story was half true; Mitchell was in the clubhouse with him, but was still in uniform when he was called to pinch hit.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Despite the rush, the rookie utility man came through with a single of his own, advancing Carter to second and putting the tying runs on base with Knight, now the potential winning run, coming up.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Schiraldi got two quick strikes on the Mets' third baseman, who had already driven in one run so far.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] However, with his team within one strike of that elusive championship, he could not finish the job as Knight singled to left-center.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Carter scored from second standing up and the speedy Mitchell advanced to third.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Finally, McNamara decided his closer had seen enough and called for the veteran Stanley to try to close out the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Some later speculated as to why Stanley, who had been warmed up by the time the tenth inning began, had not been called upon earlier instead of McNamara asking for a third inning out of Schiraldi, who had already blown the save in the eighth.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Mets' next batter was Wilson, who had recorded one hit and reached on a fielder's choice after the bad throw by Gedman in the ninth.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Six pitches into the at-bat, with the count even at two balls and two strikes, Stanley threw a breaking ball that broke sharply inside and bounced in front of Wilson, who fell down trying to avoid it.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Gedman tried to field the ball but could not, and it rolled to the backstop.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] From his knees, Wilson signaled to Mitchell to come down from third and he scored easily, tying the score at five.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Knight advanced to second on the wild pitch.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Several times during the ensuing series of pitches, second baseman Barrett realized that Knight was straying too far from the base and that if he could get Stanley to turn and throw to him, he would have an easy pickoff play and the inning could have ended there.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Despite his best attempts, Barrett never was able to get Stanley to hear him as the sellout crowd at Shea Stadium was drowning him out, and Stanley instead chose to focus on getting Wilson out.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] On the tenth pitch of the at-bat, Stanley finally got Wilson to put the ball in play, forcing a ground ball to first base.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Buckner had been playing near the foul line to give himself a better chance to get the speedy Wilson out on a ground ball, but when he went to field the ball it went under his glove and through his legs into right field.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Knight scored from second, completing the rally and giving the Mets a 6–5 victory to tie the series and force a seventh game.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the 2011 ESPN Films documentary *Catching Hell*, Buckner explained how, years after the event, he realized from watching a television replay how he had missed the ball.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He said, when he played in the field, he liked to wear a very loose glove – i.e. one that was floppy.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] When he moved to his left to try to field Wilson's grounder and then stopped, the momentum of the leftward-moving loose glove caused the glove to close.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The ball then went just past the right side of the glove.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In his 2023 appearance with Rich Eisen, Hernandez remarked that, because Buckner had spent a significant part of his career playing in the National League, he was more than familiar with Wilson and his baserunning speed.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] As such he took his normal position near the line to give himself the best chance to get the out at first; Hernandez said that if it was any other hitter in the Mets lineup but Wilson, Buckner would have been able to get the out.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After the top of the tenth, NBC began setting up in the visiting clubhouse for what they believed was the inevitable postgame victory celebration.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Commissioner's Trophy had been brought into the Red Sox clubhouse along with several bottles of champagne, team co-owner/president Jean Yawkey and pitcher Bruce Hurst (who had already been named the series MVP by the sportswriters) with Bob Costas ready to preside over the presentation.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] However, after Stanley's wild pitch in the bottom of the tenth, everything was quickly struck and removed from the room before the Red Sox returned.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Costas later recalled the removal of all the equipment for the postgame celebration as being "like a scene change in a Broadway musical.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In 2011, MLB Network ranked this as the third greatest game of the preceding 50 years.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] It was the last World Series game to end on an error until Game 4 of the 2020 World Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the years that have followed, many fans regardless of team allegiance consider Game 6 of the 1986 World Series to be one of the greatest games ever played in the history of professional baseball.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the hours that followed the end of Game 6, a rainstorm passed over the New York metropolitan area.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The field at Shea Stadium was rendered unplayable and Game 7 was postponed one night, moving to Monday, October 27.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The pitching matchup was originally supposed to feature Ron Darling, the starter for Games 1 and 4 who had yet to allow an earned run in the World Series, going up against Oil Can Boyd, who started and lost Game 3 by giving up six runs.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The rainout offered a chance for both managers to adjust their pitching strategies if they desired.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Mets manager Davey Johnson, who had employed a three-man rotation for the series consisting of Darling, Dwight Gooden, and Bob Ojeda, chose to stick with Darling, who would be pitching on his normal four days rest.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Red Sox manager John McNamara, however, decided to change his plans.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The rainout enabled Bruce Hurst, who had only allowed two runs against the Mets in his wins in Games 1 and 5, to get a third day of rest before the series ended; since he was now available to use as a starter again, McNamara opted to start him ahead of Boyd.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After Boyd received word he was not starting the final game of the series, he went down into the visitors' clubhouse and remained in there alone for some time.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] McNamara dispatched pitching coach Bill Fischer to find Boyd, and Fischer discovered that the Oil Can had consumed a great deal of alcohol and was in no condition to function, much less play.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Fischer moved Boyd into the manager's office where he locked the door and left him for the entire game.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the 500th game played in World Series history, Boston got to Darling early, recording three runs in the second inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Dwight Evans and Rich Gedman hit back to back home runs to lead the inning off and with two out, Wade Boggs drove in Dave Henderson with a single for a 3–0 Red Sox lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Gedman's home run was noteworthy for several reasons: It occurred on the first pitch after a delay of just over three minutes during which portable stands down the first base line had to be restored after several fans reaching for a foul ball had caused them to collapse.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The subsequent pitch by Darling, which came on a two-strike count (1–2), led to Gedman's home run.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] However, the ball was almost caught by Darryl Strawberry, who was reaching over the right-field wall.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Fortunately for the Red Sox, the ball fell out of Strawberry's glove and cleared the fence for a 2–0 Boston lead.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Mets, meanwhile, could not muster much against Hurst and through three innings had only recorded one hit.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the fourth Henderson reached after Darling hit him with a pitch.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After Spike Owen flew out, Hurst laid down a bunt that moved Henderson into scoring position.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Johnson then lifted Darling from the game and brought in Sid Fernandez to face Boggs and the leading hitter of the series, Marty Barrett.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Boggs managed to draw a walk, but Fernandez retired Barrett on a fly ball to right field to end the inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Mets still did not have an answer for Hurst through the fourth and fifth innings, going down in order in both frames.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Red Sox, conversely, went down in order against Fernandez in the fifth and sixth, which kept the deficit at three.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the bottom of the inning, the Mets were finally able to break through against their series nemesis and turn the tide in their favor.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After Hurst got the first out when Rafael Santana grounded out, Lee Mazzilli came up to pinch-hit for Fernandez and singled.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Mookie Wilson followed with a single of his own, and second baseman Tim Teufel drew a walk to load the bases.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Keith Hernandez then drove the lead runners in with a single, and Wally Backman came in to run for Teufel representing the tying run.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Gary Carter was the next batter and he lifted a fly ball to Evans in right.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The veteran outfielder had to dive in order to catch it, and was unable to come up with the catch.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Right field umpire Dale Ford did not immediately rule that there was no catch, which crossed up Hernandez on the basepath; since the ball was ruled to be in play, he had to attempt to advance to second base.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Since there was a delay in the ruling, Evans was able to throw back into the infield and force out Hernandez at second.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Backman managed to score on the play to tie the game, but the Mets lost the opportunity to have Darryl Strawberry come up with a chance to drive in the go ahead run; instead, Hurst got him to fly out and escaped further damage.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Hurst was lifted for a pinch hitter after this inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Roger McDowell entered the game for the Mets in the seventh and retired pinch-hitter Tony Armas, Boggs, and Barrett in order.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] McNamara called upon Game 6 loser Calvin Schiraldi to pitch the home half of the inning, despite his struggles in the extended outing he had two nights earlier.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The day of rest did not help, as he immediately surrendered a home run to Ray Knight (playing in what would be his final game as a Met) leading off, giving the Mets their first lead of the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Lenny Dykstra came up as a pinch-hitter and singled, then advanced to second on a wild pitch and scored on a single by Santana.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After McDowell successfully moved Santana into scoring position, McNamara decided to take the ball from Schiraldi and brought in Joe Sambito.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After putting Wilson on intentionally, Sambito walked Backman to load the bases and Hernandez followed with a sacrifice fly to score Santana and give the Mets a three-run advantage.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Bob Stanley recorded the final out by getting Carter to ground out to Owen at shortstop.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Down to their last six outs, Boston had not had a runner reach base since Boggs' walk in the fourth inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Jim Rice had recorded the last Red Sox hit, a single in the third, but had been thrown out trying to stretch it into a double.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] They tried to rally against McDowell in the eighth and Bill Buckner led the inning off with a single.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Rice followed with another single, and Evans doubled after that to make the score 6–5 and bring Gedman to the plate with the potential go-ahead run.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Needing to stop the rally, Johnson pulled McDowell in favor of his closer Jesse Orosco to face the Red Sox catcher.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After inducing a line drive to second that Backman caught for the first out, Orosco struck out Henderson for the second out and then got Don Baylor, batting for Owen, to ground out and end the Boston rally.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In the bottom of the eighth, the Mets finally were able to put the game away at the expense of Game 4 loser Al Nipper.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Strawberry led the inning off with a solo home run, and Knight singled and advanced to second on a groundout by Dykstra.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Santana was intentionally walked to get to the pitcher's spot, but Orosco not only came to bat but also managed to drive Knight in as he swung away on a fake bunt attempt to extend the lead back to three.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Steve Crawford then came in to face Wilson and hit him, loading the bases.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Backman then grounded into a force retiring Santana, and Hernandez grounded out and ended the inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Staked to an 8–5 lead, Orosco faced Ed Romero, who took over at shortstop for Owen in the eighth, to start the top of the ninth and retired him on a foul pop.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Boggs then grounded out to Backman at second, leaving Barrett as the last hope for the Red Sox.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Orosco worked a 2–2 count before getting Barrett to swing and miss, then tossed his glove high into the air and dropped to his knees as the Mets all converged on the mound to celebrate their world championship victory.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] McDowell was awarded the victory, with Orosco garnering his second save of the series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Schiraldi was saddled with the loss for the second consecutive game, having been charged with all three runs the Mets scored in the seventh in one-third of an inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He gave up seven runs in his final two outings of the series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Due to the rainout, this game coincided with another sporting event taking place in the New York metropolitan area that night.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The New York Giants were taking on the Washington Redskins at Giants Stadium on *Monday Night Football*, with the kickoff happening approximately thirty minutes after Game 7 started.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Many of the fans at the football game, which sold out, were following along with the baseball game and cheering loudly during high points of the game.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] When Orosco recorded the final out, the Giants were driving late in the third quarter and a collective roar went up from the crowd as the stadium scoreboard operator flashed “METS WIN” on the board to inform the fans of the result.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Giants would later win Super Bowl XXI, following in the Mets lead in winning their championship.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The World Series MVP was awarded to Ray Knight, who led the Mets' regulars with nine hits and a .393 average in the series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He also recorded five runs batted in, second to Gary Carter's nine.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Marty Barrett, in a losing effort, recorded 13 hits – tying the single World Series record – and a .433 average.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Dave Henderson recorded ten hits and a .400 average, while Jim Rice and Wade Boggs each had nine hits.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Despite the struggles both pitchers faced in Game 7, both Bruce Hurst and Ron Darling were the best starting pitchers on their respective staffs during the World Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Both finished with 2–0 records and sub-2.00 ERAs, with Darling's 1.35 ERA topping Hurst's 1.96 although Hurst issued fewer walks and struck out more batters.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Hurst had been voted MVP prior to the Mets' Game 6 comeback, but that comeback, and the Mets' Game 7 victory, kept Bobby Richardson of the 1960 New York Yankees as the only World Series MVP from a losing team.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The only other starter to win a decision was Bob Ojeda.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Steve Crawford won Game 2 for the Red Sox while Rick Aguilera and Roger McDowell won Games 6 and 7 for the Mets.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In fact, the record for the starting pitchers for both teams outside of Darling and Hurst was 1–4, with two of those losses recorded by Mets ace Dwight Gooden.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] His counterpart on the Red Sox, eventual Cy Young Award winner Roger Clemens, did not record a decision in either of his starts.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Both the Mets and Red Sox would go without reaching the World Series for some time.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Red Sox would not return until 2004, where they would finally break through and win their first title since 1918.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] They have gone on to win three additional world championships, most recently in 2018.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] As of 2024, this remains the most recent time the Red Sox have lost a World Series title.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Mets have returned to the World Series twice since 1986.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In 2000, the first time since 1956 that two teams from the same city faced each other in the World Series, the Mets lost to the New York Yankees.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The Mets returned in 2015, only to lose again to the Kansas City Royals.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Neither Davey Johnson nor John McNamara would manage in another World Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Johnson stayed on with the Mets until 1990, leading them to another postseason berth in 1988 that ended with a loss to the Los Angeles Dodgers in the National League Championship Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Johnson would later lead the Cincinnati Reds to the playoffs in 1995, then followed that with two more playoff runs with the Baltimore Orioles in 1996 and 1997.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He finished his managerial career in 2013 with the Washington Nationals.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] McNamara returned for 1987 with the Red Sox, but the team regressed significantly, finishing with only 78 wins.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He would be fired the next year with the Red Sox barely above .500 at the All-Star break, and his successor Joe Morgan led the team to a comeback and division title.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He would take over the Cleveland Indians in 1990, but was fired midway through 1991 with the team at 25–52.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He would only manage once more after that, an interim position with the California Angels in 1996, before retiring.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Bill Buckner never did win that elusive World Series ring.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He would be released by the Red Sox during the 1987 season, then spend the rest of the year with the California Angels.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In 1988, he signed with the Kansas City Royals and played more of a reserve role for the last three years of his career, which ended in 1990 after a second stint with the Red Sox.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Buckner's error made him a scapegoat in Red Sox fans' eyes for some time afterward, but following their world championship victory in 2004 the fanbase began to embrace him again.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In his later years, Buckner developed Lewy body dementia, and he died from complications at the age of 69 in May 2019.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Hedge fund manager and current Mets owner, Steven A.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Cohen, revealed in an interview that he currently owns the Buckner ball from Game 6.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] He has stated that he would donate the ball to the Mets Museum at Citi Field.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In 2020, ESPN named the 1986 World Series the fourth greatest of all time.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] On September 14 and 15, 2021, ESPN premiered *Once Upon a Time in Queens*, its four-part *30 for 30* documentary about the 1986 World Series, the Mets' seasons leading up to it and the aftermath.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Because of the involvement of both of the Yankees' rivals (both their traditional one and their cross-city counterparts), this World Series was called "(George) Steinbrenner's nightmare".
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] As a result, then-Yankee owner George Steinbrenner wrote articles in the *New York Post* during this Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] After seven years, this would be the final World Series to use the logo introduced in the 1980 series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Beginning the next year, a new logo in the style of a baseball diamond was introduced.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The logo itself would receive minor updates throughout the years.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] In 1992, gold lettering was added which would remain for the rest of its tenure until it was retired altogether after the 1997 series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] NBC's broadcast of Game 6 did not end until 12:32 a.m.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Eastern, causing the first cancellation of an episode of NBC's *Saturday Night Live* in the show's history.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] The episode, hosted by Rosanna Arquette and scheduled to air live at 11:30 p.m.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] Eastern, was instead recorded for the studio audience beginning at 1:30 a.m., and aired November 8 with a comedic apology from Ron Darling.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p01] NBC's broadcast of Game 7 (which went up against a *Monday Night Football* game between the Washington Redskins and New York Giants held at nearby Giants Stadium on ABC) garnered a Nielsen rating of 38.9 and a 55 share, making it the highest-rated single World Series game to date.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In the 1998 film *Rounders*, Matt Damon's character (Mike McDermott) references Game 6 while returning into Teddy KGB's place in the final scene.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In the 2005 film *Fever Pitch*, the main character played by Jimmy Fallon, a die hard Red Sox fan, watches a tape of the ending to Game 6 to get over what looks to be his break up with his girlfriend.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] The term "Curse of the Bambino" was not in common use by the press during the 1920s, nor can it be found through the 1970s, as a search of historical newspapers will illustrate.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In fact, even though Vecsey's articles mention a "Babe Ruth Curse", the *New York Times* did not use the phrase "Curse of the Bambino" until 1990, the year that Dan Shaughnessy's book of the same name and a *Boston Globe* article about it were published.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] Shaughnessy's book *The Curse of the Bambino* helped that phrase become a key part of the Red Sox lore in the media thereafter.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] The dramatic sixth game was the subject of *Game 6*, a 2005 independent film starring Michael Keaton, based on a 1991 screenplay by novelist Don DeLillo.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In his song "Faith and Fear in Flushing Meadows", twee/folk artist Harry Breitner makes mention of Ray Knight and Mookie Wilson.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] The game, or more specifically an infamous jeer that was issued in the game against Darryl Strawberry, was referenced in *The Simpsons* episode "Homer at the Bat" where Bart and Lisa jeer Strawberry the exact same way due to being sore over his forcing Homer to remain on the bench.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] NBC's telecast of the Series ended with the song "Limelight" from *Stereotomy*, a penultimate album of The Alan Parsons Project.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] The Series, and especially Game 6, were referenced in the *Seinfeld* episode "The Boyfriend", which also guest starred former Mets player Keith Hernandez.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] Hernandez being referred to Game 6 in the episode suggested that he was part of the winning rally, even though he was the 2nd (and final) out of the inning, though Hernandez was a big part of the prior round's Game 6 rally in the 9th inning.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In a 1999 episode of *The King of Queens* ("Rayny Day"), Doug Heffernan promises Richie Ianucci that they will watch the Series that is being rerun on TV, only to abandon him for Ray Barone, who invites him to play golf (with Arthur Spooner tagging along) until a rainstorm ends their plans.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In another episode from the same year ("Where's Poppa?"), Doug and his cousin Danny bring up the Series while revisiting their high school years.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In the *Curb Your Enthusiasm* episode "Mister Softee", Bill Buckner appears as a guest star and mocks his famous 1986 mishap by missing a crucial catch of a Mookie Wilson-signed baseball.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] As the episode concludes, he redeems himself by catching a baby thrown from a burning building.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In 2001, playwright David Kruh had his play *Curse of the Bambino* premiere at the Boston Lyric Stage.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] After the 2004 World Series it was rewritten with a happier ending.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In Ron Darling's book, *108 Stitches*, he claims that during Game 3.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] Lenny Dykstra used racial epithets toward Oil Can Boyd.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In the 2005 film *Bewitched* starring Will Ferrell and Nicole Kidman, there's a scene in which Jack (Ferrell) asks Isabel (Kidman) if her parents were in the witch business, Isabel answered that both her parents are and that her mother fixed the 1986 World Series.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] In the *Boy Meets World* episode "Career Day" Cory is embarrassed by his dad Allen's presentation of his career as a grocer in front of the class.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] When he talks to Shawn about this in the lunchroom, he references the Bill Buckner play.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] "Do you remember that uh, that World Series game where the first baseman let that EASY ground ball go under his legs and his team lost and he was humiliated in front of the entire world?
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] (Shawn replies "Yeah?") I envy his son." Later in the episode, Allen uses the same analogy while talking to his wife at home.
[src:designated-hitter/1986-world-series-p02] "Do you remember the World Series where that first baseman let that grounder dribble through his uh, legs?
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The **designated hitter** (**DH**) is a baseball player who bats in place of the pitcher.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Unlike other players in a team's lineup, they generally only play as an offensive player and usually do not play defense as a fielder or a pitcher during a game.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Due to their specialized offensive-only role, the designated hitter is generally expected to produce above average offensive stats and production compared to other players who play defense.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In Major League Baseball, the position is authorized by Rule 5.11 of the Official Baseball Rules.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] It was adopted by the American League in 1973 and by the National League in 2022, making it universal in MLB.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Within that time frame, nearly all amateur, collegiate, and professional leagues worldwide adopted the designated hitter or some variant, a major exception being Nippon Professional Baseball's Central League, which plans to adopt it in 2027.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The designated hitter is a player who does not play a position in the field, but instead replaces the pitcher in the batting order.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] However, a starting pitcher (but not relievers) may choose to also start as the designated hitter so that the pitcher bats for himself.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The DH may only be used for the pitcher (and not any other position player) as stated in Rule 5.11.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Use of the DH is optional, but must be determined before the start of the game.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] If a team does not begin a game with a DH, the team's pitchers (or pinch hitters) must bat for the entire game.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The designated hitter can be moved to a fielding position during the game.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] If the DH is moved to another position, his team forfeits the role of designated hitter, and the pitcher or another player (the latter possible only in case of a multiple substitution) would bat in the spot of the position player replaced by the former DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] If the designated hitter is moved to pitcher, any subsequent pitcher (or pinch-hitter thereof) would bat should that spot in the batting order come up again (except for a further multiple substitution).
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Likewise, if a pinch-hitter bats for a non-pitcher, and then remains in the game as the pitcher, the team would forfeit the use of the DH for the remainder of the game, and the player who was DH would become a position player (or exit the game).
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] If that player starts the game as a designated hitter and pitches out of the bullpen, the team would lose the designated hitter once his relief appearance is over, unless he is moved to another position on the field.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The exception was added by MLB for the 2022 season, coincident with the introduction of the universal DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The rule change was subsequently applied for international-level games, starting with the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Unlike other positions, the DH is "locked" into the batting order.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] No multiple substitution may be made to alter the batting rotation of the DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In other words, a double switch involving the DH and a position player (with the exception of players started as starting pitcher and designated hitter) is not legal.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] For example, if the DH is batting fourth and the catcher is batting eighth, the manager cannot replace both players so as to have the new catcher bat fourth and the new DH bat eighth.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Once a team loses its DH under any of the scenarios already discussed, the double switch becomes fully available, and may well be used via necessity, should the former DH be replaced in the lineup.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In Major League Baseball, during interleague play between 1997 and 2021, the DH rule was applied to a game based on the rules of the home team's league.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] If the game was played in an American League park, the designated hitter could be used; in a National League park, the pitcher must bat or else be replaced with a pinch-hitter.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] On June 12, 1997, San Francisco Giants outfielder Glenallen Hill became the first National League DH in a regular-season game, when the Giants met the American League Texas Rangers at The Ballpark in Arlington in interleague play.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] At first, the DH rule was not applied to the World Series.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] From 1973 to 1975, all World Series games were played under National League rules, with no DH and with pitchers required to bat.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] For 1976, it was decided the DH rule would apply to all games in the World Series, regardless of venue, but only in even-numbered years.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Cincinnati Reds first baseman Dan Driessen became the first National League designated hitter in the postseason; he was the DH in all four World Series games that year.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Beginning in the 1986 World Series, the DH rule was used in games played in the stadium of the American League representative.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] There was initially no DH in the All-Star Game.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Beginning in 1989, the rule was applied only to games played in American League stadiums.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] During this era, if the All-Star Game was scheduled for an American League stadium, fans would vote for the DH for the American League's starting lineup, while the National League's manager decided that league's starting DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Since 2010, the designated hitter has been used by both teams, regardless of where the game is played.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] This was because in the non-DH games, pitchers would rarely actually bat and would usually be replaced by pinch hitters.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Since the National League now uses the DH, it is included in the All-Star voting similar to how it had already been included in American League voting.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] For the 2021 All-Star Game, MLB granted an exception to the DH rule because Los Angeles Angels' Shohei Ohtani was selected as both starting DH and starting pitcher.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Ohtani started the game as both a pitcher and the DH and was replaced as pitcher after one inning but remained in the game as the DH without the American League having to forfeit the use of a DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The American League would have lost the DH if either Ohtani, or a player replacing him at DH, had played a position in the field other than pitcher.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The rationale for the designated hitter rule arose early in the history of professional baseball.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] During the 1880s, an increased emphasis on improving the specialized skill of pitching contributed to a decline in pitcher batting averages.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 1891, during negotiations surrounding the merger of the American Association and National League, team executives J.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Walter Spalding of New York and William Chase Temple of Pittsburgh proposed competing ideas to eliminate the pitcher from the batting order.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Temple's proposal "favored the substitution of another man to take the pitcher's place at the bat when it came his turn to go there," while Spalding proposed removing the pitcher's turn from the batting order, reducing its length to eight players.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Temple's proposal was voted down by a narrow margin prior to the 1892 season.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The idea of a designated hitter was raised by Philadelphia Athletics manager Connie Mack in 1906; however, his proposal received little support.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Pitchers rejected the idea of giving up hitting.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Several managers were interested in the idea and intended to implement it during spring training in 1929.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] However, Heydler's proposal was not adopted as an official rule change, and he advised teams to have pitchers bat during spring training in order for them to prepare for the regular season.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Serious momentum to implement the designated hitter was absent until the pitching dominance of the late 1960s.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 1968, Bob Gibson led the major leagues with a live-ball era record 1.12 ERA.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] For the first time since 1908, the American and National Leagues had a collective batting average below .240; Carl Yastrzemski led the American League in hitting with only a .301 mark.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] After the season, in order to increase offensive output, the height of the pitcher's mound was reduced from 15 to 10 inches (38 to 25 cm), and the upper limit of the strike zone was lowered from the top of a batter's shoulders to his armpits.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 1969, the International League and four other minor leagues began a four-year trial period for the designated hitter.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The American League allowed its use in spring training in 1971, however, when the minor league trial period ended, the American and National Leagues could not agree on implementation.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Like other experimental baseball rule changes of the 1960s and 1970s, the DH was embraced by Oakland Athletics owner Charlie O.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] On January 11, 1973, Finley and the other American League owners voted 8–4 to approve the designated hitter for a three-year trial run.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The National League chose not to implement the DH; it was intended for the two leagues to agree on a common rule at the end of the American League's trial.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] On April 6, 1973, Ron Blomberg of the New York Yankees became the first designated hitter in MLB history, facing Boston Red Sox right-hander Luis Tiant in his first plate appearance.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Blomberg was walked on five pitches with the bases loaded in the first inning.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] As expected, the American League posted a higher batting average than the National League in 1973.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] This trend held in every season in which the American League employed the designated hitter but the National League did not between 1973 and 2021.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] At the end of its three-year trial period, the American League kept the designated hitter, while the National League still refused to adopt it.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In response to increases in American League attendance because of the DH, the National League held a vote on August 13, 1980, to determine whether or not to adopt it.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] A majority of the 12 member teams was necessary to pass the rule, and the measure was expected to pass.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] However, when the teams were informed that the rule would not take effect until the 1982 season, Philadelphia Phillies vice president Bill Giles was unsure of how the team owner, Ruly Carpenter, wanted him to vote.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Unable to contact Carpenter, who was on a fishing trip, Giles was forced to abstain from voting.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Prior to the meeting, Harding Peterson, general manager for the Pittsburgh Pirates, was told to side with the Phillies however they voted.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The final tally was four teams voting for the DH (the Atlanta Braves, New York Mets, St.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Louis Cardinals, and San Diego Padres), five votes against (the Chicago Cubs, Cincinnati Reds, Los Angeles Dodgers, Montreal Expos, and San Francisco Giants), and three abstentions (the Phillies, Pirates, and Houston Astros).
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Five days after that meeting, the Cardinals fired their general manager, John Claiborne, who was the leading proponent for the adoption of the DH rule, and the National League never held another vote on the issue.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The designated hitter was not used in the World Series from 1973 to 1975.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Between 1976 and 1985, the DH was used in the World Series during even-numbered years, while pitchers batted in odd-numbered years.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 1986, the rule was changed to implement designated hitters only in World Series games in which the home team was from the American League.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] This rule was also adopted for interleague play during the regular season upon its introduction in 1997.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] As time passed, the designated hitter rule enabled American League managers to employ diverse strategies in setting their teams' lineups.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Managers could rotate the DH role among part-time players (for example, using a left-handed batter against a right-handed pitcher and vice versa), or they could employ a full-time designated hitter against all pitchers.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Healthy regular lineup players gained the ability to take a partial day off by not playing the field, while aging, injured, and injury prone players gained the opportunity to bat without being exposed to re-injury while fielding.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] By 2009, only a handful of players compiled over 400 at-bats as a DH each year.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] This trend continued, even with the eventual onset of the universal designated hitter.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The Astros moved to the American League in 2013, giving each league 15 teams and requiring interleague play throughout the entire season.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] There was debate within MLB to unify the rules of the two leagues, with either the American League returning to its pre-1973 rules and having the pitcher hit or the National League adopting the DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In January 2016, MLB commissioner Rob Manfred indicated that consideration was given to the National League adopting the DH for the 2017 season, when a new collective bargaining agreement would take effect.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] However, he later backtracked, saying that he did not envision such a change being made in the near future.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Accordingly, the DH rule was not then adopted by the National League.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2020, in an attempt to avoid overtaxing pitchers and lessen the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic, the National League used the DH for the first time.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] For the first time since 1972 (the final year before the American League adopted the DH), the National League had the higher seasonal batting average of the two leagues.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] At least one of the proposals released during negotiations between MLB and the Major League Baseball Players' Association (MLBPA) regarding the 2021 season's rules included the so-called "universal DH," but an impasse led to a temporary return to National League pitchers hitting in that year.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] On April 4, 2021, an American League team voluntarily declined to use a designated hitter in their starting lineup for the first time since 1976, when the Los Angeles Angels placed starting pitcher Shohei Ohtani second in the batting order.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] This was also the first time since 1903 that a pitcher had been listed as the second hitter in the starting lineup.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] On June 23, 2021, Ohtani made history again when, for the first time, an AL team did not use the designated hitter and an NL team did.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] While the Angels declined the DH privilege, the visiting Giants opted to use it, starting Alex Dickerson at DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] On February 10, 2022, Manfred announced plans for a universal DH beginning with the 2022 season.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The rule was ratified as part of a new collective bargaining agreement with the MLBPA on March 10, 2022, after which both leagues have continuously employed the designated hitter.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The designated hitter rule has been the subject of debate both before and after its implementation.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Supporters of the rule have cited its original intent, to replace weak-hitting pitchers in the batting order, and the potential for added excitement due to the associated increase in offense.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Critics have cited the asymmetry of creating a position that is not required to hit and field.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Older players who are weak fielders or have a history of injuries have been able to extend their careers by becoming designated hitters, as the position is less physically demanding than those that involve playing the field.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The designated hitter rule also changes managerial strategy, particularly in late innings.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Without the DH, a manager must decide whether to let a pitcher bat or to substitute a pinch hitter.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] If a pinch hitter is used, then the manager must decide whether that hitter will stay in the game after batting, and if so, at what position.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] When the decision to remove a pitcher is made, the manager may also use the double switch, a substitution mechanism in which the new pitcher adopts a different position in the batting order than the previous pitcher.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The double switch is typically employed to delay the new pitcher's first plate appearance.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The designated hitter reduces the need for late-inning pinch hitters and eliminates the principal utility of the double switch entirely.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Prior to the introduction of the universal DH, interleague play caused teams to adjust their usual strategies for lineup and roster construction.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 1993, John Olerud, who had won that year's American League batting title, was benched in the third game of the World Series, played in a National League stadium, when designated hitter Paul Molitor took Olerud's typical position at first base.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2003, ESPN writer Jayson Stark claimed that the San Francisco Giants may have lost the previous year's World Series because their roster was not optimized for the use of a DH in the home stadium of their American League opponents.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Similarly, after the Central League champion Yomiuri Giants were swept in the 2019 Japan Series, manager Tatsunori Hara said that the addition of the designated hitter gave teams in the Pacific League an advantage when developing pitchers.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] When regular season interleague play was introduced to Major League Baseball, multiple proposals were made to remove the DH from the American League in order to maintain consistency across both leagues.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Until the introduction of the universal DH, the American League held a distinct advantage over the National League during interleague play in most seasons.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The ability of American League teams to increase the depth of their lineups with designated hitters contributed to this trend.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] When the games were played in AL parks, the NL team had to put a bench player into the lineup.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] When the games were played in NL parks, even though the AL team had to take a player out of their lineup, that left them with a starting player available to pinch-hit and/or come in as a substitute player later in the game, as opposed to a bench player on the NL team.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Occasionally, injuries sustained by pitchers were cited to support the expansion of the DH to the National League.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2008, New York Yankees pitcher Chien-Ming Wang was injured while running the bases in an interleague game against the Houston Astros.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Wang was diagnosed with a torn Lisfranc ligament and a partial tear of the peroneus longus of the right foot.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Wang's subsequent extensive rehabilitation prevented him from being an effective major league pitcher after the injury.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] He subsequently said that while he enjoyed hitting, he favored consistency between the leagues, remarking, "Who would people rather see, a real hitter hitting home runs or a pitcher swinging a wet newspaper?
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The Baseball Writers' Association of America presents an annual award to the outstanding designated hitter of the season, called the Edgar Martínez Award.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Renamed for the former Seattle Mariners DH after his retirement in 2004, the award was introduced in 1973 and has been given every season since, except 1994 due to the players' strike.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Multiple winners include David Ortiz (eight times), Martínez (five times), and Shohei Ohtani (four times).
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] DHs have generally not had much impact on the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award or National Baseball Hall of Fame voting, because of the relative rarity of the full-time DH and the DH not contributing defense.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2021, Shohei Ohtani became the first everyday DH to win league MVP honors, having played in 126 of 155 games (81.29%) at DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] However, Ohtani's MVP season was mainly due to his success as a two-way player, having also logged 23 games as a pitcher and seven games in the outfield.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2023, Ohtani won his second MVP award, playing 134 of 135 games as a DH that season while also pitching in 23 of those games.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2024, Ohtani, now with the Los Angeles Dodgers in the National League, won his second consecutive MVP award, the first time the award was given to a player who exclusively played as a DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Due to Tommy John surgery on his pitching elbow, Ohtani only played as a DH in 2024.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Ohtani won his third consecutive MVP award in 2025, returning to two-way form with 47 innings in 14 starts as a pitcher in addition to 158 appearances as a DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] During the 1993 season Paul Molitor became the first player to win the World Series Most Valuable Player Award, while playing 137 of 160 games (85.63%) as a DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Hideki Matsui (2009), David Ortiz (2013), and Jorge Soler (2021) were the only other DHs to win World Series MVP.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Soler, playing for the Atlanta Braves, was the only DH to win the award while a member of a National League team.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In games played at National League parks, Ortiz and Molitor played at first base, while Soler played in right field.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] However, Matsui became the only World Series MVP to never play in the field that season, as he came in as a pinch hitter in the pitcher's spot but was never moved to a fielding position via a double switch during games played in a National League park.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Ortiz was also the first designated hitter to win the ALCS MVP in 2004, followed by Delmon Young in 2012, and Yordan Alvarez in 2021.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2025, Shohei Ohtani became the first designated hitter to win NLCS MVP, though he also appeared in six innings as a pitcher.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Among Hall of Famers, Paul Molitor and Jim Rice were, until 2014, the only inductees to even have played at least 25% of their games at DH, though Molitor played more games at DH than any other position during his career.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2014, Frank Thomas became the first Hall of Famer who played the majority of his games at DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2019, Edgar Martínez and Harold Baines were inducted into the Hall of Fame.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Martinez played over 70% of his games at DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Baines played more than half of his games at DH, playing only 63 games in the field between 1989 and the end of his career in 2001.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2022, David Ortiz became the first full-time DH to be elected to the Hall of Fame on his first ballot.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Prior to 2020, only one designated hitter Silver Slugger Award was awarded, and only American League players were the recipients due to the National League awarding a pitcher Silver Slugger Award.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2020, and since 2022, both American and National Leagues began awarding Silver Slugger Awards for designated hitters.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The first National League DH Silver Slugger Award was given to Marcell Ozuna in 2020.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Martinez became the first and to date only player to win two Silver Slugger Awards in the same season, winning as both a designated hitter and a left fielder.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Japan's Pacific League adopted the designated hitter in 1975, two years after its adoption in the American League.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Japan's Central League has not adopted the designated hitter – the only top-level professional league in the world to refrain from doing so.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In August 2025, the six owners of Central League teams unanimously voted to adopt the DH beginning in 2027.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] When teams from different leagues play against each other in interleague games or the Japan Series, the DH rule is currently adopted if the Pacific League's team hosts the game, similar to the MLB rules before the universal DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The Mexican League introduced the designated hitter in 1974, one year after the American League.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The Cuban National Series adopted the designated hitter in 1977.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The KBO League introduced the designated hitter in 1982.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The DH is used for all Minor League Baseball (MiLB) games.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Prior to the adoption of the DH by the National League in 2022, only Rookie and Single-A level leagues used the DH rule in all games, while Double-A and Triple-A games, when both teams were National League affiliates the designated hitter was not used.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The reason for the difference was that as players get closer to reaching the majors, teams preferred to have the rules mimic those of the major league teams for which the players may soon be playing.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The Atlantic League, an independent minor league that became an MLB Partner League after the 2021 MiLB reorganization, implemented an experimental "double-hook rule" for its 2021 season.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Under this rule, once a team removes its starting pitcher it loses the right to use a DH for the rest of the game.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The "double hook" rule was modified for the 2022 Atlantic League season.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] The change allows a team whose starting pitcher goes at least five innings to keep its DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In American high schools and other amateur baseball leagues that use National Federation of State High School Associations (NFHS) rules, a DH may bat in place of one player in any position, not just a pitcher.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Many coaches use a designated hitter in place of the weakest hitter in the lineup, if they use one at all.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In amateur baseball, many pitchers are also good hitters and will often play another position (or even DH) when not pitching.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In 2020, NFHS rules were modified to also add a "Player/DH" rule where a player may start the game with offensive and defensive roles, and be substituted out only on defense while remaining in the game on offense as a DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Japanese high school baseball was, for a long time, one of the few amateur baseball leagues in the world to never use the designated hitter rule at all.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] It was not until the 2026 rulebook update that the designated hitter rule was introduced, with the 2026 Spring Koshien tournament being the first major tournament to adopt the rule.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In high school baseball in South Korea, the rule has been adopted since 2004.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] American Legion rules, on the other hand, allow the DH only to bat for the pitcher; prior to 1995, the use of the DH was not allowed in Legion baseball at all.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In college baseball, NCAA rules state that the designated hitter must hit for the pitcher, but in many instances the pitcher is also a good hitter, and the coach may elect to let the pitcher bat in the lineup.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] If the pitcher opts to bat for himself, he is treated as two separate positions – a pitcher and a designated hitter (abbreviated P/DH on the lineup card) – and may be substituted for as such (i.e. if he is removed as the pitcher, he may remain as the designated hitter and vice versa).
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] Conversely, a player who begins the game as the DH, but not as the pitcher, may come into the game as a reliever and remain as the DH (in effect becoming a P/DH), be relieved on the mound later in the game but continue to bat as the DH.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] In Little League Baseball, the DH is not used except in the Senior League (age 15–16) division, where the DH can bat in place of any defensive player.
[src:designated-hitter/designated-hitter] However, a league may adopt a rule which requires all players present and able to play to be listed in the batting order (such that the order contains more than nine players), and thus all players will have a turn to bat even when they are not assigned a fielding position.
